    "search_text": "Jef D. Boeke Professor Leads a synthetic genomics and genome writing program focused on designing, assembling, and installing very large DNA constructs to interrogate genome regulation and build faithful disease models. Synthetic genomics Genome writing Genome engineering Large DNA assembly Landing pads Cre RMCE CRISPR Cas9 mSwAP In YAV Big DNA Chromatin regulation Functional genomics Institute for Systems Genetics Mammalian genome writing Yeast homologous recombination Assemblons Big IN Landing pad integration Cre lox RMCE CRISPR Cas9 genome editing Mouse embryonic stem cells Transgenic mouse engineering Human locus humanization TAF1 X linked dystonia parkinsonism SVA retrotransposon elements Transcription elongation roadblocks HPRT1 Default genomic states Synthetic yeast chromosomes 3D genome organization Chromatin profiling RNA sequencing ATAC sequencing Hi C CAGE sequencing Automation and robotics for DNA assembly Assemblatron Jack In the Box vector system SURE vector system",
    "lab_synopsis": "Leads a synthetic genomics and genome writing program focused on designing, assembling, and installing very large DNA constructs to interrogate genome regulation and build faithful disease models. Develops genome writing pipelines that combine yeast based assembly of multi segment loci with targeted delivery into yeast and mouse embryonic stem cells using strategies such as Big IN and mSwAP In. Uses these capabilities to build tailored mammalian disease models, including a genomically rewritten TAF1 humanization model of X linked dystonia parkinsonism that links intronic SVA elements to transcriptional defects and neurodegeneration. Applies synthetic locus designs such as reversed human HPRT1 to define default genome states and to probe transcriptional and chromatin activity across episomal and integrated contexts in yeast and mouse. Builds and automates big DNA assembly workflows, including Assemblatron and ultra low background yeast vectors, enabling scalable assembly and verification of 50 kb and larger constructs. Also explores how synthetic genome architecture shapes nuclear organization and gene regulation, including manipulation of the 3D organization of large synthetic yeast chromosomes.",
    "summary_short": "Leads a synthetic genomics and genome writing program focused on designing, assembling, and installing very large DNA constructs to interrogate genome regulation and build faithful disease models. Develops genome writing pipelines that combine yeast based assembly of multi segment loci with targeted delivery into yeast and mouse embryonic stem cells using strategies such as Big IN and mSwAP In.",
