      "2018-Delarue-Cell_anonymous.pdf"
    ],
    "common_experiments_raw": "GEMs-Based Microrheology\n* Genetically encoded nanoparticle tracking to measure intracellular viscoelasticity, crowding, and active matter across organelles\nMechanical Perturbation Systems\n* Compression devices, tunable synthetic hydrogels, and osmotic manipulation to control cellular mechanical environment\nLive-Cell Single-Particle Tracking\n* High-throughput fluorescence microscopy with computational analysis of molecular diffusion and dynamics\nSynthetic Biology & Protein Engineering\n* Design of synthetic condensates (SynDrops), engineered transcription factors, and AI-designed proteins\nReal-Time Metabolic Biosensors\n* ATP and pH sensors for live monitoring of cellular energetics"
  },
  {
    "id": "intake_molly_gale_hammell",
    "name": "Molly Gale Hammell",
    "title": "Associate Professor",
    "summary": "Molly Gale Hammell is an Associate Professor in the Institute for Systems Genetics at NYU Langone Health.",
    "keywords": [],
    "search_text": "Molly Gale Hammell Associate Professor Molly Gale Hammell is an Associate Professor in the Institute for Systems Genetics at NYU Langone Health.",
    "lab_synopsis": "Molly Gale Hammell is an Associate Professor in the Institute for Systems Genetics at NYU Langone Health. Her research portfolio centers on computational and quantitative genetic approaches, focusing on the regulation and function of transposable elements in the human genome, RNA biology, and data-driven studies of neurodegeneration, particularly Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS). She is recognized for her contributions to developing novel statistical and algorithmic tools for genomic data analysis and for uncovering mechanisms that drive disease processes at the genetic and molecular level. Her interdisciplinary expertise spans genetics, genomics, systems biology, and human disease, positioning her at the forefront of research that connects mechanistic insights to translational and clinical relevance. More recently, her lab has been exploring the ability of transposable elements derived RNA and DNA species to activate innate immune pathways, driving neuroinflammation.\n\nMolly Gale Hammell is an Associate Professor in the Institute for Systems Genetics at NYU Langone Health. Her research portfolio centers on computational and quantitative genetic approaches, focusing on the regulation and function of transposable elements in the human genome, RNA biology, and data-driven studies of neurodegeneration, particularly Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS). She is recognized for her contributions to developing novel statistical and algorithmic tools for genomic data analysis and for uncovering mechanisms that drive disease processes at the genetic and molecular level. Her interdisciplinary expertise spans genetics, genomics, systems biology, and human disease, positioning her at the forefront of research that connects mechanistic insights to translational and clinical relevance. Current interests include neuroinflammatory triggers driven by transposable elements and innate immune pathways",
    "summary_short": "Molly Gale Hammell is an Associate Professor in the Institute for Systems Genetics at NYU Langone Health. Her research portfolio centers on computational and quantitative genetic approaches, focusing on the regulation and function of transposable elements in the human genome, RNA biology, and data-driven studies of neurodegeneration, particularly Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS).",
    "research_keywords": [],
    "affiliations": [
      "Institute for Systems Genetics (ISG)",
      "Neuroscience and Physiology"
    ],
    "focus_groups": [
      "Organoids"
    ],
    "common_experiments_raw": "Stem cell modeling through iPSC differentiation into neurons, astrocytes, and microglia. CRISPR mediated manipulation of gene expression (CRISPRi, CRISPRa). Genomics and epigenomics profiling of cells and postmortem tissues (RNA-seq, MeDIP-seq, Cut&Run, MeRIP-seq, long-read-RNA-seq, nuc-seq, scRNA-seq). Single-cell analysis. AI-driven data analysis. Tissue & cell staining with immunofluorescence and IHC.\n\nGenomics, Epigenomics, and Transcriptomics (RNA-seq, Cut&Run, MeDip-seq, MeRIP-seq, Iso-seq). Single-cell genomics (snRNA-seq, scRNA-seq, nuc-seq). iPSC-derived culture of neurons, astrocytes, and microglia. Neural 3D organoid culture. CRISPR mediated gene manipulation (CRISPRi, CRISPRa). Bioinformatics. Multi-omics integration. Analysis of transposons (TEs) and endogenous retroviruses (ERVs). Machine learning methods development."
  },
  {
    "id": "intake_paolo_mita",
    "name": "Paolo Mita",
    "title": "Research Assistant Professor",
    "summary": "Transposable elements (TE) are sequences of DNA that are capable of moving within a host genome, and thus are often referred to as “jumping genes.” DNA transposons use a “cut and paste” mechanism to move within a host genome while retrotransposons increase their amount using a “copy and paste” process.",
    "keywords": [],
    "search_text": "Paolo Mita Research Assistant Professor Transposable elements (TE) are sequences of DNA that are capable of moving within a host genome, and thus are often referred to as “jumping genes.” DNA transposons use a “cut and paste” mechanism to move within a host genome while retrotransposons increase their amount using a “copy and paste” process.",
    "lab_synopsis": "Transposable elements (TE) are sequences of DNA that are capable of moving within a host genome, and thus are often referred to as “jumping genes.” DNA transposons use a “cut and paste” mechanism to move within a host genome while retrotransposons increase their amount using a “copy and paste” process.  My research focuses on the study of the Long Interspersed Element-1 (LINE-1 or L1) retrotransposon, which is the only TE capable of autonomously \"jumping\" within the human genome.   I seek to advance the basic understanding of L1 retrotransposon physiology in human cells and explore its role in human diseases and processes, such as cancer, aging and wound healing. Specifically, we aim to identify and study the impact of L1 proteins, mRNA expression and activity on a variety of cellular mechanisms, including DNA damage and replication, cellular ploidy during tumor evolution, viral sensing pathways, and the deregulation of tumor suppressors and oncogenes.   To achieve these goals, we use a multidisciplinary approach that integrates genetic, microscopy, and proteomic techniques in both in vitro and in vivo mouse models. By leveraging these tools, we are mechanistically characterizing the impact of L1 on cellular physiology. This knowledge has the potential to inform the development of novel therapeutic and diagnostic approaches, thereby contributing to improved clinical outcomes.  More recently I am also involved in the development and implementation of new synthetic biology and cell engineering approaches applied to the protection and restoration of endangered bird species.",
    "summary_short": "Transposable elements (TE) are sequences of DNA that are capable of moving within a host genome, and thus are often referred to as “jumping genes.” DNA transposons use a “cut and paste” mechanism to move within a host genome while retrotransposons increase their amount using a “copy and paste” process. My research focuses on the study of the Long Interspersed Element-1 (LINE-1 or L1) retrotransposon, which is the only TE capable of autonomously \"jumping\" within the human genome.",
    "research_keywords": [],
    "affiliations": [
      "Biochemistry and Molecular Pharmacology",
      "Institute for Systems Genetics (ISG)",
      "Microbiology"
    ],
    "common_experiments_raw": "Cell culture \nWestern blotting\nLINE-1 retrotransposition assays\ncell cycle measurement\naneuploidy quantification\ngrowth assays\nscratch assays\nimmunofluorescence\nmammary fat pad injection\nCRISPR screens\ngenome engineering\nproteins over-expression\ngene knock down \ncell sorting\nflow cytometry measurements"
  },
  {
    "id": "intake_ran_brosh",
    "name": "Ran Brosh",
    "title": "Research Assistant Professor, Associate Director",
    "summary": "I have two roles: [1] as Faculty at ISG/Pathology I am leading the Dark Matter Project, a collaborative effort to use synthetic biology and genome writing to study the noncoding genome and its roles in health and disease.",
    "keywords": [
      "ACE2 humanized mouse models",
      "Big IN platform",
      "CRISPR activation rescue",
      "DHS element function mapping",
      "SARS CoV 2 susceptibility models",
      "SVA retrotransposon biology",
